In version 1.2.10 or earlier we passed an object (shown in the script) as parameter for the sort, it appears that worked-around the issue. However since version 1.2.11 a type check is added.

To demonstrate this issue I build a CLI script:
{code:php}
<?php

// setup collection
$m = new \Mongo();
$db = $m->test;
$coll = $db->test_sort;

// insert test data
for ($i=0; $i<10; $i++) {
    $coll->insert(array('0' => 'a' + $i, '1' => 'b' + $i, '2' => 'c' + $i), array('safe' => true));
}

// ask user on which 'column' to sort
$column = readline('Sort on: ');
$sort = ('asc' === readline('How ("asc" or "desc", default desc): ')) ? 1 : -1;

// query and sort
$cursor = $coll->find()->sort(array($column => $sort));

// the line below is a workaround for 1.2.10 or earlier, it casts the array to an object.
//$cursor = $coll->find()->sort((object) array($column => $sort));

// print
foreach ($cursor as $record) {
    unset($record['_id']);
    $line = json_encode($record);
    echo "{$line}\n";
}
echo "\n";

// cleanup
$coll->drop();
{code}

To reproduce *expected* behavior:
{code:bash}
php -f <above_script>
> Sort on: 1
> How ("asc" or "desc", default desc): desc
{code}

To reproduce *unexpected* behavior:
{code:bash}
php -f <above_script>
> Sort on: 0
> How ("asc" or "desc", default desc): desc
{code}

